	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I'm afraid most of you are missing the main point about this game.  Verant allows people to solo, but everything they do with the game is geared towards grouping.  So if you're upset that your pets don't do enough damage, that's becuase it was designed to work along with the tanks in your group, just as the spells they cast work in tandem with your group.  A mage's spell list compliments the spells available to the other classes that you'll be grouping with, you may think them crap, but when utilized in a group setting they tend to be appropriate and powered enough to make the game challenging.  It seems that many of you complaining have never even gotten to 60, do you even know if there is a use for Banishment?  I would assume there would be or Verant wouldn't have put it in. Yes, they tend to be frugal with experience, loot, spell damage, melee damage....etc, but that's because they want the game to be very challenging to a 'group' and virtually impossible for 'soloers'.  Many may not like that, including myself, but that's a core aspect of EQ that will never change.  The only true soloer in the game is the Necro, not even the Druid can compare and that is because of the general purpose fear spell, but they pay the price by being kos and not being as party oriented or party friendly in their spell selections.  They also don't do as well in dungeons as they do outdoors, just like the druid.  Mages by far, are much more party oriented and generally play a bigger role in dungeons than either of the soloing classes and the price you pay for that is with the more limited spell selection and pets that will always perform less than a true tank.  Verant just designed mages for limited soloing and there is no amount of whining you can do to change that unless you can get them to make the game itself more solo friendly and that would mean for all the classes.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
